  "teacher_notes": [
    "Emphasize the importance of identifying like terms BEFORE combining. Students should circle or underline like terms.",
    "Common error: trying to combine unlike terms like \\(x^2 + x \\ne 2x^2\\) or \\(2x\\). Reinforce that only like terms can be combined.",
    "When distributing a negative sign: EVERY term inside changes sign. Use examples like \\(-(3x - 5) = -3x + 5\\) repeatedly.",
    "Dropping variables is common: \\(2x + 5x = 7x\\) (not \\(7\\)). Emphasize keeping the variable part.",
    "For nested parentheses: teach students to work from the innermost parentheses outward, one layer at a time.",
    "Standard form convention: write terms in decreasing order of exponents: \\(x^2\\) before \\(x\\) before constants."
  ]
